1
00:00:24,090 --> 00:00:26,524
[Man Narrating ]
You may have heard
the story of Helen,

2
00:00:26,626 --> 00:00:31,222
a woman whose beauty
launched a thousand ships...

3
00:00:32,499 --> 00:00:36,367
and started the most famous
war in history.

4
00:00:36,469 --> 00:00:39,336
You may have heard
of that valiant struggle...

5
00:00:39,439 --> 00:00:43,000
that took place beneath
the golden walls of Troy.

6
00:00:43,109 --> 00:00:46,875
Ten years, the best of our lives.

7
00:00:46,980 --> 00:00:48,971
Ten thousand men,

8
00:00:49,082 --> 00:00:52,711
the best the gods and dreams
of glory could have fashioned.

9
00:00:55,188 --> 00:00:58,749
All led by my brother Agamemnon,

10
00:00:58,858 --> 00:01:01,486
the mightiest of the Greeks.

11
00:01:05,632 --> 00:01:09,864
And Achilles, who could
strike down 10 warriors with one blow.

12
00:01:15,008 --> 00:01:18,034
You may even have heard of Paris,

13
00:01:18,144 --> 00:01:21,272
who they say betrayed
his country and crown...

14
00:01:21,381 --> 00:01:23,440
for love.

15
00:01:23,550 --> 00:01:27,077
But that is not
the way it happened.

16
00:01:27,187 --> 00:01:32,147
Let me tell you the real story.
I know. I was there.

17
00:01:39,632 --> 00:01:40,894
[ Girl ]
Kill him!

18
00:01:45,371 --> 00:01:48,067
KiIl him!

19
00:01:51,211 --> 00:01:54,374
[ Woman Groaning ]
KiIl him! KiIl him!

20
00:01:54,481 --> 00:01:59,214
KiIl him! KiIl him!
KiIl him!

21
00:01:59,319 --> 00:02:01,219
[ Baby Crying ]

22
00:02:01,321 --> 00:02:04,415
[ Woman ]
It's a boy, Your Highness.
A boy!

23
00:02:04,524 --> 00:02:07,550
[ Crying Continues ]

24
00:02:07,660 --> 00:02:11,756
You said, "KiIl him. KiIl him."

25
00:02:11,865 --> 00:02:15,164
Before any of us knew that it was a boy.

26
00:02:15,268 --> 00:02:19,170
Cassandra, have you just had
one of your visions, hmm? TelI me!

27
00:02:19,272 --> 00:02:22,139
Priam, come see your son.

28
00:02:22,242 --> 00:02:26,042
Cassandra, come see
your brother Alexandros.

29
00:02:26,146 --> 00:02:30,048
Look, Cassandra, Cassandra...

30
00:02:30,150 --> 00:02:33,916
I know that you see things,
and I know that people don't believe you, but I do.

31
00:02:34,020 --> 00:02:37,956
You-You saw that
it was a baby boy, right?

32
00:02:38,057 --> 00:02:42,255
Hmm? What else did you see?
[ Panting ]

33
00:02:42,362 --> 00:02:44,626
What else?

34
00:02:44,731 --> 00:02:48,792
If he lives, Troy will burn.

35
00:02:56,943 --> 00:03:00,538
[ Crying Continues ]

36
00:03:00,647 --> 00:03:03,207
Take my son to the mountain.

37
00:03:03,316 --> 00:03:05,341
No!

38
00:03:05,451 --> 00:03:07,612
Throw him from the highest peak.

39
00:03:07,720 --> 00:03:09,620
No! Do it now!

40
00:03:09,722 --> 00:03:14,352
No! No!
No, no, no, no!

41
00:03:14,460 --> 00:03:17,896
No! No! Please!

42
00:03:17,997 --> 00:03:22,627
No! Please! My son!

43
00:03:22,735 --> 00:03:24,635
No!

44
00:03:49,629 --> 00:03:51,824
Gods, do your will.

45
00:04:00,039 --> 00:04:03,133
[ Baby Crying ]

46
00:04:10,817 --> 00:04:15,720
Why would they? 
What was it, child?

47
00:04:15,822 --> 00:04:19,485
Some foul prophet
jealous of your beauty?

48
00:04:19,592 --> 00:04:24,086
Never mind. With me
you shall be loved and honored.

49
00:04:24,197 --> 00:04:27,257
I shall name you... Paris.

50
00:04:31,471 --> 00:04:35,430
[Man ] Paris! Paris, where are you?

51
00:04:37,010 --> 00:04:39,740
Paris, come! Time to eat!

52
00:04:46,653 --> 00:04:49,121
[ Laughing ]

53
00:04:51,224 --> 00:04:55,126
[ Grunting ]

54
00:04:57,563 --> 00:04:59,827
- Ohhh!
- [ Laughs ]

55
00:05:03,536 --> 00:05:06,403
I've got goats who fight better than you.

56
00:05:06,506 --> 00:05:10,567
Hey, too bad you can't
watch your goats as well as your flank.

57
00:05:10,677 --> 00:05:12,736
Look!
What?

58
00:05:12,845 --> 00:05:16,645
- [ Goat Bleating ]
- Watch my herd!

59
00:05:20,953 --> 00:05:24,252
Stubos!

60
00:05:27,427 --> 00:05:30,021
[ Bleating ]

61
00:05:43,576 --> 00:05:45,874
[ Bell Clanking ]

62
00:05:51,284 --> 00:05:53,718
Stubos!

63
00:06:01,327 --> 00:06:04,490
[ Bell Ringing ]

64
00:06:06,866 --> 00:06:09,596
[ Goat Bleating]

65
00:06:26,619 --> 00:06:28,519
Stubos?

66
00:06:46,706 --> 00:06:50,233
[ Water Flowing]

67
00:06:50,343 --> 00:06:52,243
Stubos?

68
00:07:19,505 --> 00:07:21,939
[ Sighs ]

69
00:07:23,643 --> 00:07:27,044
[ Indistinct Whispering]

70
00:07:27,146 --> 00:07:29,046
Who's there?

71
00:07:33,486 --> 00:07:36,148
Beauty is all; all is beauty.

72
00:07:36,255 --> 00:07:38,917
Victory goes to the strong.

73
00:07:39,025 --> 00:07:42,051
Gold rules men.
Wealth is power.

74
00:07:45,665 --> 00:07:48,896
Paris must choose.

75
00:07:50,636 --> 00:07:54,800
You must judge who of us is fairest.

76
00:07:57,109 --> 00:07:59,009
Who are you?

77
00:07:59,111 --> 00:08:02,410
Choose me, Paris.
I am Hera.

78
00:08:02,515 --> 00:08:05,746
I can give you wealth
beyond your dreams.

79
00:08:05,852 --> 00:08:09,413
Athena brings victory
and glory forever.

80
00:08:15,862 --> 00:08:20,925
Look into its face, Paris.
See what Aphrodite gives.

81
00:08:24,437 --> 00:08:28,032
The most beautiful
woman in the world--

82
00:08:31,210 --> 00:08:33,110
Helen.

83
00:09:26,999 --> 00:09:29,559
[ Horse Whinnies ]

84
00:09:51,857 --> 00:09:54,849
[ Horse Whinnies ]

85
00:09:54,961 --> 00:09:58,192
- Pollux!
- You know you can't go outside the city walls.

86
00:09:58,297 --> 00:10:00,765
Father is furious.

87
00:10:02,535 --> 00:10:04,765
Come on. Let's get you bathed and dressed.

88
00:10:04,870 --> 00:10:08,271
You can't go to a wedding looking like that. 
That big one in front.

89
00:10:08,374 --> 00:10:12,003
Is that Agamem-- the one
who's to marry our sister?

90
00:10:12,111 --> 00:10:14,705
No. That's his father, King Atreus.

91
00:10:14,814 --> 00:10:17,044
See that one there with the beard?

92
00:10:17,149 --> 00:10:21,449
That's Agamemnon.
They say that one day he will rule the entire Aegean.

93
00:10:21,554 --> 00:10:24,717
Now come on. Let's go.
Who's the other one, the young one?

94
00:10:24,824 --> 00:10:28,123
[ Pollux ] 
That's his brother, Menelaus.
Younger by two years.

95
00:10:28,227 --> 00:10:31,458
And not too fond ofliving
in his brother's shadow, so I hear.

96
00:10:31,564 --> 00:10:33,828
Com e on.
Let's get you dressed.

97
00:10:33,933 --> 00:10:35,992
Where are they from?
Mycenae.

98
00:10:36,102 --> 00:10:39,265
Where's that?
Never you mind.

99
00:11:02,161 --> 00:11:06,359
Theseus, my king, this is
bad timing, don't you think?

100
00:11:06,465 --> 00:11:08,490
The greater the challenge.

101
00:11:09,101 --> 00:11:11,160
Don't get me wrong.
I love a challenge.

102
00:11:11,270 --> 00:11:14,000
But I just hate to be missing Athens
in the springtime.

103
00:11:14,106 --> 00:11:15,664
You know how
beautiful that is.

104
00:11:15,775 --> 00:11:19,336
If you want beauty,
you'll find it right here
beyond those walls.

105
00:11:19,445 --> 00:11:22,346
The most beautiful girl
in the world is here in Sparta.

106
00:11:22,448 --> 00:11:24,507
She's just a child!

107
00:11:24,617 --> 00:11:27,609
I'll ripen her like grapes.
I'll age her like wine.

108
00:11:27,720 --> 00:11:30,052
When she ages just enough,
I'll taste her.

109
00:11:30,122 --> 00:11:34,354
Well and fine, but not when 
the greatest warriors in Mycenae
are just behind those walls.

110
00:11:34,460 --> 00:11:36,894
Don't be such a bore.
Let's have some fun.

111
00:11:36,962 --> 00:11:40,523
Fun? This is not fun.
Fishing is fun.

112
00:11:40,633 --> 00:11:42,533
Playing the lute is fun.

113
00:11:42,768 --> 00:11:45,100
Swimming in shark-infested
waters is fun.

114
00:11:45,204 --> 00:11:47,866
Committing suicide
is not fun!

115
00:11:49,408 --> 00:11:52,206
[ Blowing Horn ]

116
00:12:30,950 --> 00:12:36,217
High King Atreus,
Prince Agamemnon,
Prince Menelaus.

117
00:12:36,322 --> 00:12:38,517
We welcome you to Sparta.

118
00:12:38,624 --> 00:12:42,924
Great Tyndareus,
made greater by his kindness.

119
00:12:43,028 --> 00:12:47,931
Made greater
only by his most dutiful
and obedient daughter.

120
00:12:48,033 --> 00:12:51,434
May I present
the lovely Clytem nestra.

121
00:12:57,910 --> 00:13:00,378
Clytem nestra...

122
00:13:00,479 --> 00:13:05,416
I hereby claim you
as my wife.

123
00:13:16,262 --> 00:13:18,093
And who is this?

124
00:13:20,766 --> 00:13:23,792
My youngest.
Still a child.

125
00:13:23,903 --> 00:13:28,169
An untamed
and disrespectful child,
I might add.

126
00:13:30,176 --> 00:13:32,474
Her name, my lord?

127
00:13:32,578 --> 00:13:34,273
She is Helen.

128
00:13:38,284 --> 00:13:40,514
Helen.

129
00:13:42,288 --> 00:13:44,483
Father, I will take her
to her room.

130
00:13:44,590 --> 00:13:46,490
Yes, indeed you shall.

131
00:13:46,592 --> 00:13:50,585
As punishment for her disrespect,
she will miss the wedding feast.

132
00:13:53,933 --> 00:13:56,026
Father-In-Law,

133
00:13:56,135 --> 00:13:59,662
I see my bride is distressed.

134
00:13:59,772 --> 00:14:01,831
You're quite right.

135
00:14:01,941 --> 00:14:05,377
Clytemnestra's little sister
is but a child--

136
00:14:05,477 --> 00:14:07,468
a child who meant no harm.

137
00:14:07,580 --> 00:14:11,175
Why not invite her
to join us?

138
00:14:11,283 --> 00:14:13,843
Well, that sounds fair.

139
00:14:17,756 --> 00:14:22,193
I would be honored
to be Helen's escort,

140
00:14:22,294 --> 00:14:25,354
should the king's
legendary kindness permit.

141
00:14:26,966 --> 00:14:30,333
Pollux, see that
she's properly dressed.

142
00:14:30,436 --> 00:14:32,336
Yes, Father.

143
00:14:33,739 --> 00:14:36,537
Have you ever seen
anything like it?
So much trouble.

144
00:14:38,744 --> 00:14:40,644
[Helen ]
What's all the fuss about?

145
00:14:40,746 --> 00:14:43,772
Don't you understand
anything about anything?

146
00:14:43,883 --> 00:14:46,511
You're not a little girl.
You're--

147
00:14:46,619 --> 00:14:49,349
You're almost a woman.
What are you doing?

148
00:14:49,455 --> 00:14:52,720
I'm no such thing.
You are. Listen.
Listen to me.

149
00:14:52,825 --> 00:14:55,589
Get off for a second.
Listen!
No! I won't!

150
00:14:55,694 --> 00:14:57,093
Helen!

151
00:14:59,298 --> 00:15:01,892
Helen, I love you
more than life.

152
00:15:02,001 --> 00:15:04,026
I know it's hard to accept,

153
00:15:04,136 --> 00:15:06,934
but someday soon
you will marry.

154
00:15:07,039 --> 00:15:09,633
I already know who to.

155
00:15:09,742 --> 00:15:11,937
You do?
I saw him.

156
00:15:12,044 --> 00:15:14,842
Where?
In the water.

157
00:15:14,947 --> 00:15:17,575
You'll marry a fish?
A shepherd.

158
00:15:17,683 --> 00:15:20,015
Oh, that's likely.
Helen!

159
00:15:20,119 --> 00:15:24,021
I will. I will, Pollux.
I had a vision.

160
00:15:24,123 --> 00:15:26,990
I saw his face and--
And what?

161
00:15:27,092 --> 00:15:29,617
He saw mine.

162
00:15:29,728 --> 00:15:32,663
And one day he'll find me.

163
00:15:32,765 --> 00:15:35,199
I know it.

164
00:15:35,301 --> 00:15:39,203
I just-- I know it.
[ Laughs ]

165
00:15:39,305 --> 00:15:42,297
Good. Good.

166
00:15:42,408 --> 00:15:46,538
Meanwhile, you must be ready
for kings and princes
to seek your hand.

167
00:15:46,645 --> 00:15:50,046
Why?
Your beauty,
your spirit.

168
00:15:50,149 --> 00:15:53,084
It makes men weak.

169
00:15:55,187 --> 00:15:59,556
Helen, you have no idea
what madness lies in men.

170
00:15:59,658 --> 00:16:01,956
All men, every one.

171
00:16:02,061 --> 00:16:04,393
Even you?

172
00:16:13,906 --> 00:16:16,238
&& [Middle Eastern ]

173
00:16:18,877 --> 00:16:21,345
There she is.
Ah, yes, I see her.

174
00:16:32,024 --> 00:16:35,687
[ Woman Laughing]

175
00:16:55,748 --> 00:17:00,310
[ Chattering ]

176
00:17:37,790 --> 00:17:40,486
[ Gasps, Screams ]

177
00:17:43,095 --> 00:17:46,997
[ Muffled Screaming ]

178
00:17:49,468 --> 00:17:52,437
- Halt there!
- Would you hold this, please?

179
00:17:52,538 --> 00:17:55,701
Thank you.
[ Grunting ]

180
00:17:55,808 --> 00:17:58,572
[ Screaming Continues ]

181
00:18:43,922 --> 00:18:45,981
[Helen ]
Whyareyou doing that?

182
00:18:46,091 --> 00:18:48,116
Doing what?

183
00:18:48,227 --> 00:18:51,924
Casting lots.
And I know what for too.

184
00:18:55,234 --> 00:18:57,725
You've no right.
I'm not some sort of a prize--

185
00:18:57,836 --> 00:19:00,361
Well done, my friend.

186
00:19:00,472 --> 00:19:02,736
So you get the gi rl,
and I get the horse.

187
00:19:05,611 --> 00:19:11,345
Well, I'll just have to find meself
another stunningly beautiful princess.

188
00:19:11,450 --> 00:19:14,977
- Persephone, perhaps.
- She's sweet on pomegranates,
I heard.

189
00:19:15,087 --> 00:19:18,022
I hate pomegranates.

190
00:19:18,123 --> 00:19:20,489
Farewell, my friend.

191
00:19:20,592 --> 00:19:23,652
May the gods be kind.

192
00:19:32,571 --> 00:19:34,471
Who are you?

193
00:19:36,375 --> 00:19:38,707
Theseus, King of Athens.

194
00:19:38,810 --> 00:19:40,903
You don't look
like a king.

195
00:19:43,282 --> 00:19:45,341
[ Spits ]

196
00:19:47,386 --> 00:19:51,015
You'd better get used to me.
I'm going to marry you.

197
00:19:54,092 --> 00:19:56,652
I think you've got me
confused with my sister.

198
00:19:56,762 --> 00:20:00,596
I'm not the daughter
of Tyndareus who does
what anybody says.

199
00:20:00,699 --> 00:20:03,167
You're not the daughter
of Tyndareus at all.

200
00:20:03,268 --> 00:20:05,498
Of course I am.

201
00:20:05,604 --> 00:20:10,166
You think my mother found me
under a cabbage leaf?

202
00:20:10,275 --> 00:20:12,539
Some say that.

203
00:20:12,644 --> 00:20:14,544
I don't.

204
00:20:17,916 --> 00:20:20,077
You're Queen Leda's daughter,
all right.

205
00:20:20,185 --> 00:20:22,153
There's no mistaking
that face.

206
00:20:24,122 --> 00:20:27,091
I'm my father's
daughter too.

207
00:20:27,192 --> 00:20:30,491
[ Laughs ]
You'd have to be.
That's the way it works.

208
00:20:30,596 --> 00:20:32,723
Tyndareus is my father.

209
00:20:34,866 --> 00:20:37,858
They never told you
anything at all, did they?

210
00:20:39,972 --> 00:20:41,872
Told me what?

211
00:20:41,974 --> 00:20:44,204
What do you think
happened to your mother?

212
00:20:44,309 --> 00:20:46,209
She died.
Why?

213
00:20:48,647 --> 00:20:53,209
Because of me.
I made her sick.

214
00:20:54,486 --> 00:20:58,149
How? Do you know?

215
00:21:04,896 --> 00:21:08,127
Tyndareus told you
you killed your mother?

216
00:21:08,233 --> 00:21:11,361
He didn't have to say it.

217
00:21:14,273 --> 00:21:16,241
He can't look at me.

218
00:21:16,341 --> 00:21:19,640
[ Sighs ]
Your mother took
her own life, Helen.

219
00:21:19,745 --> 00:21:22,839
She leapt from the west wall
of the palace.

220
00:21:26,885 --> 00:21:30,787
No. You lie.

221
00:21:38,597 --> 00:21:42,124
Why would she?
She was raped.

222
00:21:44,670 --> 00:21:47,503
Because she was beautiful?

223
00:21:47,606 --> 00:21:49,506
Yeah.

224
00:21:49,608 --> 00:21:52,543
[ Helen Screams ]
Is that what you intend with me?

225
00:21:52,644 --> 00:21:54,669
What?
Rape.

226
00:21:54,780 --> 00:21:57,180
I don't rape children.
Or are you a woman?

227
00:21:57,282 --> 00:21:59,011
No. No. No.

228
00:21:59,117 --> 00:22:04,111
Well, when you are,
we'll be good friends.
You will be fine.

229
00:22:04,222 --> 00:22:07,817
[Distant Shouting]

230
00:22:18,704 --> 00:22:20,331
You can't take away
our best stock.

231
00:22:20,439 --> 00:22:23,670
You should be honored.
Honored? That you
steal away our livelihood?

232
00:22:23,775 --> 00:22:26,835
[ Woman Shouting, Indistinct ]

233
00:22:26,945 --> 00:22:30,176
You'll be com pensated.
Fairly. Fairly com pensated.

234
00:22:30,282 --> 00:22:32,307
Com pensated doesn't
fill our cows with seed.

235
00:22:32,417 --> 00:22:35,215
Com pensation doesn't
give us meat!
[ Man ] Paris, where are you?

236
00:22:35,821 --> 00:22:38,119
Paris!
They're taking your bull!

237
00:22:38,223 --> 00:22:41,556
- That's the property of the king ofTroy!
- No, he's not! He's mine!

238
00:22:41,793 --> 00:22:44,023
I raised him!
Hold it!

239
00:22:44,463 --> 00:22:48,058
- [ Grunting ]
- Leave him! Leave my son alone!

240
00:22:48,166 --> 00:22:51,033
[ Grunting, Groans ]

241
00:22:52,571 --> 00:22:54,300
[ Mooning ]

242
00:23:00,112 --> 00:23:01,909
Any other objections?

243
00:23:01,980 --> 00:23:03,845
[ Groaning Continues ]

244
00:23:12,124 --> 00:23:16,026
He will be the grand prize
in King Priam's games.

245
00:23:16,128 --> 00:23:19,359
If you wish to negotiate
with the winner,

246
00:23:19,464 --> 00:23:21,432
you will find him there.

247
00:24:09,581 --> 00:24:11,811
[ Helen ]
Tell me the truth
about my mother.

248
00:24:13,752 --> 00:24:16,744
I need to know. Please.

249
00:24:27,999 --> 00:24:30,900
[ Sighs ]

250
00:24:31,002 --> 00:24:35,336
When it happened,
Tyndareus was away in Egypt.

251
00:24:35,440 --> 00:24:38,500
When she began to show
a couple of months later,

252
00:24:38,610 --> 00:24:41,511
he'd been gone
for half a year.

253
00:24:41,613 --> 00:24:46,516
So the kingdom
watched her belly swell
month after month.

254
00:24:46,618 --> 00:24:48,916
She was disgraced.

255
00:24:49,020 --> 00:24:51,818
She had no husband
beside her.

256
00:24:51,923 --> 00:24:56,292
She waited till
she had you, then--

257
00:24:56,394 --> 00:24:59,295
Had me?

258
00:24:59,397 --> 00:25:02,628
[ Shuddering ]
It was me?

259
00:25:11,843 --> 00:25:14,107
No!

260
00:25:14,212 --> 00:25:16,703
Helen, no!
There are wolves!

261
00:25:25,991 --> 00:25:29,620
[ Sighs, Panting ]

262
00:25:32,097 --> 00:25:33,997
Do I look like her?

263
00:25:36,434 --> 00:25:40,097
Well, you're younger...
and dirtier.

264
00:25:42,407 --> 00:25:46,844
When you grow up,
if you grow up and don't
make me wring your neck,

265
00:25:46,945 --> 00:25:49,038
you'll be even more
breathtaking.

266
00:25:51,516 --> 00:25:55,748
Who was it? Who did it?

267
00:25:55,854 --> 00:25:58,345
Tell me who.

268
00:26:00,292 --> 00:26:03,420
Helen, you're the daughter
of the greatest god.

269
00:26:03,528 --> 00:26:05,894
Zeus is your father.

270
00:26:07,165 --> 00:26:09,656
That's why your beauty
will never be matched.

271
00:26:10,268 --> 00:26:12,964
That's why no man
will ever resist it.

272
00:26:17,475 --> 00:26:19,375
You resisted me.

273
00:26:21,012 --> 00:26:23,810
Well...
[ Laughs ]

274
00:26:23,915 --> 00:26:26,941
not without great effort.

275
00:26:30,922 --> 00:26:33,720
Let me be your friend.

276
00:26:35,260 --> 00:26:37,421
I think you could do with one.

277
00:26:41,166 --> 00:26:44,624
I must always
know the truth.

278
00:26:45,036 --> 00:26:47,869
Always.

279
00:26:54,212 --> 00:26:57,545
[Paris ]
I'm going to Troy.
I'll get our bull back.

280
00:26:57,649 --> 00:27:00,709
[ Father]
Troy is no place
for people like us.

281
00:27:00,819 --> 00:27:04,516
I'm going.
No. They'll hurt you.

282
00:27:07,325 --> 00:27:10,726
I f these ri bs a ren't broken,
they will be with one more blow.

283
00:27:10,829 --> 00:27:15,596
They can't treat us like that,
like we're nothing.

284
00:27:15,700 --> 00:27:20,330
I'll bring back what's ours.
There's no point.

285
00:27:20,438 --> 00:27:23,498
There is...
when I win it.

286
00:27:27,746 --> 00:27:30,078
[ Chattering ]

287
00:27:30,181 --> 00:27:32,979
[ Narrator ]
And so Paris came to Troy.

288
00:27:35,153 --> 00:27:37,678
It was the richest city in the world.

289
00:27:42,160 --> 00:27:44,685
Into it were brought
silks from Asia,

290
00:27:44,796 --> 00:27:48,357
spices from Arabia,
rare woods from Africa.

291
00:27:55,407 --> 00:27:57,568
[ Chicken Clucking ]

292
00:27:57,676 --> 00:28:00,509
[ Speaking Asian Language ]

293
00:28:06,651 --> 00:28:09,643
A feast for the eyes.
Both of them. Huh?

294
00:28:11,423 --> 00:28:14,517
[ Chattering Continues ]

295
00:28:24,469 --> 00:28:28,303
[ Narrator]
From its strategic harbor,
with its massive walls,

296
00:28:28,406 --> 00:28:32,206
Troy controlled all trade
north and south ofthe Aegean.

297
00:28:35,914 --> 00:28:39,350
And Paris would control
Troy's fate...

298
00:28:39,451 --> 00:28:42,318
more than he could know.

299
00:28:59,804 --> 00:29:02,466
[ Horse Whinnying ]

300
00:29:23,828 --> 00:29:27,127
[ Bull Mooing ]

301
00:29:31,536 --> 00:29:33,697
[ Mooing Continues ]

302
00:29:40,311 --> 00:29:43,041
[ Applause, Cheering ]

303
00:29:53,758 --> 00:29:56,522
[ Chattering ]

304
00:29:56,628 --> 00:29:59,529
[ Cheering Continues ]

305
00:30:12,243 --> 00:30:15,337
[ Crowd Chanting ]
Hector! Hector! Hector! Hector!

306
00:30:15,947 --> 00:30:17,778
You here to sign up?

307
00:30:20,251 --> 00:30:22,344
What's your name?

308
00:30:22,954 --> 00:30:25,787
Paris.
Of?

309
00:30:26,724 --> 00:30:29,158
As in where from?

310
00:30:29,260 --> 00:30:32,195
[ Applause ]
Mount Ida.

311
00:30:34,632 --> 00:30:36,862
All right.
Where's your cuirass?

312
00:30:36,968 --> 00:30:39,937
- My what?
- Breastplate.

313
00:30:40,872 --> 00:30:42,772
No?

314
00:30:42,874 --> 00:30:45,365
What about a helmet?

315
00:30:46,311 --> 00:30:48,939
Any kind of armor?

316
00:30:49,881 --> 00:30:53,749
Boy! Fetch me
some of that old armor.

317
00:30:57,355 --> 00:30:59,323
How about your cudgel?

318
00:31:01,526 --> 00:31:03,517
I could use this.

319
00:31:03,628 --> 00:31:06,358
Look here, lad,
you can't win,

320
00:31:06,464 --> 00:31:10,298
but at least you have
to put on a good show.

321
00:31:10,902 --> 00:31:13,370
Go ahead, choose one.

322
00:31:22,013 --> 00:31:25,039
You'll find some
better than others.

323
00:31:30,555 --> 00:31:33,490
Why can't I win?

324
00:31:35,226 --> 00:31:38,923
No one ever beats
Prince Hector.

325
00:31:41,633 --> 00:31:45,296
[Applause, Cheering]

326
00:31:46,070 --> 00:31:47,560
Leave your knife
on the rack.

327
00:31:51,643 --> 00:31:55,272
Hey, shepherd boy!
The hero from Mt. Ida!

328
00:31:55,380 --> 00:31:56,779
[ Laughing ]

329
00:31:56,881 --> 00:31:59,873
Ah, the king's thief.

330
00:32:00,318 --> 00:32:03,116
You're on, shepherd.
With your friend.

331
00:32:03,221 --> 00:32:04,882
Go! Go, go!

332
00:32:04,989 --> 00:32:10,222
Paris of Mt. Ida
meets Pres Byterian,

333
00:32:10,328 --> 00:32:12,694
commander ofthe guard!

334
00:32:12,797 --> 00:32:16,028
[ Cheering, Booing ]

335
00:32:23,641 --> 00:32:27,042
[ Booing, Jeering ]

336
00:32:57,275 --> 00:32:59,607
[ Both Grunting ]

337
00:33:51,329 --> 00:33:55,823
[ Grunting ]

338
00:33:55,933 --> 00:34:00,961
[ Cheering ]
[Announcer]
The winner is Paris of Mt. Ida.

339
00:34:09,447 --> 00:34:12,314
[ Groaning ]

340
00:34:15,086 --> 00:34:17,179
Need better armor.

341
00:34:17,288 --> 00:34:20,257
This old Hittite stuffisjunk.

342
00:34:22,260 --> 00:34:25,229
Is it bad?
It's nothing.

343
00:34:25,329 --> 00:34:28,730
An old wound.
You shouldn't be fighting.

344
00:34:30,168 --> 00:34:31,499
I have to.

345
00:34:31,602 --> 00:34:35,038
Oh, really?
And why is that?

346
00:34:35,139 --> 00:34:38,131
I don't like thieves
sent by kings...

347
00:34:38,242 --> 00:34:41,234
to steal my livestock
for their games and amusement.

348
00:34:43,114 --> 00:34:45,082
The bull?

349
00:34:47,118 --> 00:34:49,018
My bull.

350
00:34:49,120 --> 00:34:51,452
Ah.

351
00:34:53,224 --> 00:34:56,591
[ Laughing ]

352
00:35:00,631 --> 00:35:03,862
[ Crowd Cheering]

353
00:35:12,810 --> 00:35:14,869
My father's games
must be fair.

354
00:35:14,979 --> 00:35:17,140
I can't fight
a wounded man.

355
00:35:17,248 --> 00:35:19,910
The rules are clear,
my lord. You must.

356
00:35:22,553 --> 00:35:26,649
Paris. Son.
[ Groaning ]

357
00:35:26,757 --> 00:35:30,818
Paris of Mt. Ida
will fight Damien of Argos.

358
00:35:30,928 --> 00:35:33,419
You're hurt.
I'll be fine.

359
00:35:33,531 --> 00:35:36,295
Your ribs.
You can't.
Father, I'll be fine.

360
00:35:40,671 --> 00:35:43,401
[ Crowd Cheering]

361
00:35:57,255 --> 00:36:02,420
[ Announcer ]
The winner is Paris of Mt. Ida!

362
00:36:02,527 --> 00:36:06,088
[ Crowd Cheering]

363
00:36:06,197 --> 00:36:07,926
[ Announcer Continues ]

364
00:36:08,032 --> 00:36:13,299
Paris, you must stop this.
I've seen these
crush a man's head.

365
00:36:13,404 --> 00:36:16,965
[ Gasps ]
Paris, you must
never mind what happened.

366
00:36:17,074 --> 00:36:20,043
We'll survive
without our bull.

367
00:36:20,144 --> 00:36:22,544
Paris,
you're my only child.

368
00:36:22,647 --> 00:36:25,844
I beg you, come home.

369
00:36:25,950 --> 00:36:29,249
[ Panting ]
You raised me to be strong,

370
00:36:29,353 --> 00:36:31,685
to be loyal,

371
00:36:31,789 --> 00:36:33,916
to defend what I believe in.

372
00:36:34,025 --> 00:36:36,425
[Announcer]
Paris of Mt. Ida...

373
00:36:36,527 --> 00:36:39,621
will fight
Hideus of Seronea.

374
00:36:39,730 --> 00:36:41,630
I love you, Father.

375
00:37:00,818 --> 00:37:06,017
[Announcer]
The winner:
Paris of Mt. Ida!

376
00:37:06,123 --> 00:37:09,581
I can't watch
my only son get killed.

377
00:37:09,694 --> 00:37:12,686
He's not your son.
Begone, old shepherd.

378
00:37:12,797 --> 00:37:14,697
Wait.
He's my father.

379
00:37:14,799 --> 00:37:17,927
No, Paris, don't.
It's Princess Cassandra.

380
00:37:21,038 --> 00:37:23,063
Alexandros.

381
00:37:23,174 --> 00:37:25,768
My name is Paris.

382
00:37:30,047 --> 00:37:31,605
You should be dead.

383
00:37:32,183 --> 00:37:33,844
Give me a minute.

384
00:37:34,252 --> 00:37:36,015
[ Announcer ]
The final match!

385
00:37:36,120 --> 00:37:39,180
Prince Hector of Troy...

386
00:37:39,290 --> 00:37:43,659
against Paris of Mt. Ida!

387
00:37:44,929 --> 00:37:46,226
No!

388
00:37:46,330 --> 00:37:49,265
[ Whispering ]
You must kill him.

389
00:37:49,367 --> 00:37:51,460
These are just games,
Cassandra.

390
00:37:51,569 --> 00:37:52,627
You don't understand!

391
00:37:52,737 --> 00:37:57,003
Look, he is good,
but he's only a shepherd.
He's Alexandros.

392
00:38:00,978 --> 00:38:04,004
He's baby Alexandros!

393
00:38:13,724 --> 00:38:17,455
If you love your family,
honor Troy,

394
00:38:17,561 --> 00:38:19,688
you must destroy him.

395
00:38:34,078 --> 00:38:36,273
You don't intend to fight me?

396
00:38:37,515 --> 00:38:41,076
I'll fight you the way I live,
not Troy's way.

397
00:38:50,528 --> 00:38:53,497
Do you know how to use
a dagger, shepherd?

398
00:38:55,533 --> 00:38:58,001
Can't stop wolves with sticks.

399
00:39:05,142 --> 00:39:07,702
What is he doing?

400
00:39:22,159 --> 00:39:24,059
Then use it.

401
00:39:31,936 --> 00:39:35,770
[ Crowd Murmuring ]

402
00:39:54,525 --> 00:39:57,153
[ Both Grunting ]

403
00:40:18,682 --> 00:40:20,650
[ Grunting Continues ]

404
00:40:25,556 --> 00:40:28,457
- Kill him!
- What?

405
00:40:28,559 --> 00:40:30,789
[ Yelling ]

406
00:40:32,997 --> 00:40:35,465
Come on!

407
00:40:35,566 --> 00:40:38,501
[ Cassandra ]
Kill him! Kill him! Kill him!

408
00:40:38,602 --> 00:40:41,036
Kill him! Kill him!

409
00:40:52,216 --> 00:40:54,150
Alexandros?

410
00:41:05,896 --> 00:41:08,797
[ Screaming ]
Kill him!

411
00:41:17,374 --> 00:41:19,740
Do you surrender?

412
00:41:21,445 --> 00:41:23,470
I am prepared to die.

413
00:41:23,581 --> 00:41:25,481
I don't want your life!

414
00:41:25,583 --> 00:41:28,177
Does Prince Hector
surrender?

415
00:41:28,285 --> 00:41:30,947
Does Troy surrender?

416
00:41:34,692 --> 00:41:40,130
The winner:
Paris of Mt. Ida!

417
00:41:40,231 --> 00:41:42,631
[ Crowd Cheering]

418
00:41:54,245 --> 00:41:57,373
Approach,
Paris of Mt. Ida.

419
00:42:02,152 --> 00:42:05,087
Don't look at him, Mother.

420
00:42:05,189 --> 00:42:07,453
Alexandros?

421
00:42:11,662 --> 00:42:13,994
Are you Alexandros?

422
00:42:14,098 --> 00:42:16,498
My name is Paris.

423
00:42:17,935 --> 00:42:20,369
Father,
what are you doing?

424
00:42:20,471 --> 00:42:23,565
We have our bull.
We can go home.

425
00:42:23,674 --> 00:42:25,642
You are home.

426
00:42:29,580 --> 00:42:31,878
Noble King Priam,

427
00:42:31,982 --> 00:42:35,975
if someone must be punished,
let it be me.

428
00:42:36,086 --> 00:42:39,180
My son?
There is no doubt,
my queen.

429
00:42:41,625 --> 00:42:43,718
I found him
on the mountain.

430
00:42:51,402 --> 00:42:54,394
[ Sobs ]

431
00:42:58,609 --> 00:43:01,373
My darling, darling child.

432
00:43:08,786 --> 00:43:11,482
Shepherd...

433
00:43:11,589 --> 00:43:14,854
you've done well.

434
00:43:14,959 --> 00:43:18,019
You have brought home
our son.

435
00:43:26,003 --> 00:43:28,767
Welcome home...

436
00:43:28,872 --> 00:43:32,239
Prince Paris ofTroy!

437
00:43:32,343 --> 00:43:36,370
[ Cheering, Applause ]

438
00:43:38,649 --> 00:43:41,482
The prophecy
has been fulfilled.

439
00:43:41,585 --> 00:43:43,485
What prophecy?

440
00:43:43,587 --> 00:43:46,454
Because you live,
we all must die.

441
00:44:07,578 --> 00:44:09,478
[ Horse Nickers ]

442
00:44:09,580 --> 00:44:11,548
How was the ride?

443
00:44:19,623 --> 00:44:21,523
Ohh.

444
00:44:21,625 --> 00:44:23,456
Mount Hymettus honey.

445
00:44:23,560 --> 00:44:25,619
Best i n the world.

446
00:44:39,977 --> 00:44:42,878
How do you know
it's the best?

447
00:44:42,980 --> 00:44:45,073
Well, I suppose I don't.

448
00:44:47,418 --> 00:44:49,818
Well, then there's always a chance...

449
00:44:49,920 --> 00:44:52,047
you might find something better.

450
00:44:53,190 --> 00:44:55,158
No.

451
00:44:56,360 --> 00:44:59,523
I want to love.
Well, you will someday.

452
00:45:01,198 --> 00:45:03,029
I'm ready now.

453
00:45:03,133 --> 00:45:05,124
You're young.

454
00:45:05,235 --> 00:45:07,203
I'm a woman.

455
00:45:20,084 --> 00:45:23,679
Someday, someplace
you'll find someone better.

456
00:45:23,787 --> 00:45:26,187
Someone worthier.

457
00:45:26,290 --> 00:45:28,850
When you do,
neither the gods' will
nor the earth's turning...

458
00:45:28,959 --> 00:45:31,257
will keep you from him.

459
00:45:32,529 --> 00:45:34,497
That's how I feel
about you.

460
00:45:34,598 --> 00:45:39,331
But, Helen, this has just been--
well, a kind of practice.

461
00:45:41,805 --> 00:45:44,501
Someday
you'll know the difference.

462
00:45:47,444 --> 00:45:49,776
You always said
that we'd marry.

463
00:45:50,848 --> 00:45:52,577
Helen.

464
00:45:58,989 --> 00:46:01,082
Hey.

465
00:46:15,405 --> 00:46:17,305
[ Gasps ]

466
00:46:17,407 --> 00:46:19,432
Pollux!
Shh. Quiet.

467
00:46:22,579 --> 00:46:25,241
Why are you here?
We finally found you.

468
00:46:25,349 --> 00:46:27,078
You're safe now.

469
00:46:27,184 --> 00:46:29,812
[ Murmuring ]

470
00:46:29,920 --> 00:46:31,649
[ Shouting ]

471
00:46:31,755 --> 00:46:33,416
[ Gasps ]

472
00:46:33,524 --> 00:46:35,492
Aah!

473
00:46:37,895 --> 00:46:40,887
[ Grunting ]

474
00:46:51,542 --> 00:46:53,339
Leave him!

475
00:46:54,711 --> 00:46:56,611
Let me go!

476
00:46:56,713 --> 00:47:00,114
Let me go!
Pollux, make them stop!

477
00:47:00,217 --> 00:47:02,412
Get her out of here!
Don't let her see this!

478
00:47:02,519 --> 00:47:04,282
It will warm her heart!

479
00:47:04,388 --> 00:47:06,253
No, Pollux!
You don't understand!

480
00:47:07,958 --> 00:47:10,518
Get off me!
[ Grunts ]

481
00:47:12,129 --> 00:47:13,528
Aah!

482
00:47:13,630 --> 00:47:15,530
[ Grunting Continues ]

483
00:47:37,554 --> 00:47:40,717
Pollux, if you love me,
hear me!

484
00:47:47,798 --> 00:47:49,663
Let me go!

485
00:47:51,134 --> 00:47:52,658
No!
It's all right, Helen!

486
00:47:52,769 --> 00:47:56,398
I t's a fai r price,
and I gladly pay it.

487
00:47:58,342 --> 00:48:00,242
- [ Groans ]
- No!

488
00:48:06,650 --> 00:48:09,813
[ Whimpering ]
No!

489
00:48:19,263 --> 00:48:22,198
- [ Grunts ]
- Pollux!

490
00:48:22,299 --> 00:48:24,665
- No!
- [ Helen Screaming ]

491
00:48:30,374 --> 00:48:32,774
[ No Audio ]

492
00:48:35,879 --> 00:48:38,848
[ Narrator]
With the death of Pollux,
Tyndareus had no heir.

493
00:48:38,949 --> 00:48:41,315
The great kings
of the Aegean...

494
00:48:41,418 --> 00:48:44,819
were drawn to Sparta
like moths to the flame.

495
00:48:44,922 --> 00:48:48,824
Odysseus, king of Ithaca,
remembers the fallen Pollux...

496
00:48:48,926 --> 00:48:51,952
and offers his heart
to the great king
Tyndareus.

497
00:48:59,269 --> 00:49:01,601
Achilles brings greetings
from the Myrmidons...

498
00:49:01,705 --> 00:49:05,106
who stand shoulder to shoulder
with the people of Sparta...

499
00:49:05,208 --> 00:49:07,108
to defend the honor of Sparta...

500
00:49:07,210 --> 00:49:11,010
and to revenge the blood
of the great king Tyndareus.

501
00:49:16,053 --> 00:49:20,114
To die for a woman--
it's hard to imagine
such weakness.

502
00:49:20,190 --> 00:49:21,623
You cannot comment.
You have not seen her.

503
00:49:21,692 --> 00:49:23,785
- I don't need to.
- [ Scoffs ]

504
00:49:24,227 --> 00:49:27,526
- You afraid to try?
- I'm afraid of nothing.

505
00:49:28,665 --> 00:49:30,633
There.

506
00:49:33,136 --> 00:49:35,969
You shed no tears.

507
00:49:36,073 --> 00:49:39,201
By your actions,
you have left me
without love or hope...

508
00:49:39,309 --> 00:49:41,470
and Sparta without
its future king,

509
00:49:41,578 --> 00:49:43,671
and you show no grief.

510
00:49:43,780 --> 00:49:46,510
[ Tyndareus ]
It should have been you
who died.

511
00:49:56,259 --> 00:50:00,286
Is there any among you
who will take
this cursed woman?

512
00:50:01,765 --> 00:50:03,665
Is there
any among you...

513
00:50:03,767 --> 00:50:06,736
who wishes their home devastated,

514
00:50:06,837 --> 00:50:09,237
his country brought to ruin,

515
00:50:09,339 --> 00:50:12,604
his heart broken beyond repair?

516
00:50:16,646 --> 00:50:19,615
I leave her to you.

517
00:50:27,891 --> 00:50:29,859
Leave her!

518
00:51:01,825 --> 00:51:03,725
Tyndareus is right.

519
00:51:03,827 --> 00:51:07,263
She'll bring her husband
more trouble
than he could ever imagine.

520
00:51:07,364 --> 00:51:12,392
[ Odysseus ]
The path to her bed
is strewn with ash and death.

521
00:51:12,502 --> 00:51:18,099
And yet is there not one man
'round this table
who does not want her?

522
00:51:18,208 --> 00:51:21,700
Do you suggest that
every king here draw his sword
against the other?

523
00:51:24,948 --> 00:51:27,280
No. Of course not.
That would be--

524
00:51:27,384 --> 00:51:29,818
What he wants is to
have her all to himself.

525
00:51:29,886 --> 00:51:33,083
Isn't that right,
little brother?
[ Kings Laughing]

526
00:51:38,028 --> 00:51:41,156
In truth, if we raise
our swords at all,

527
00:51:41,264 --> 00:51:44,165
it should be together
and pointed
in the same direction.

528
00:51:44,267 --> 00:51:46,167
Toward riches
in Byzantium.

529
00:51:46,269 --> 00:51:47,998
Or Perseus.

530
00:51:48,105 --> 00:51:51,006
If we unite,
we can conquer
anything at all.

531
00:51:51,108 --> 00:51:53,440
Any creature,
any nation.

532
00:51:53,543 --> 00:51:56,137
Well spoken, Agamemnon,
but you control no army.

533
00:51:57,747 --> 00:52:00,147
Perhaps I should
tellyou, brothers,
that as we speak...

534
00:52:00,250 --> 00:52:02,411
our father,
the clear-eyed Atreus,
lies alone,

535
00:52:02,519 --> 00:52:04,544
speaking only
with the gods.

536
00:52:04,654 --> 00:52:09,182
In a matter of days they
will take him, and I will return
to the citadel at Mycenae.

537
00:52:09,626 --> 00:52:12,356
[Achilles ]
Then let us greet you now
as our new high king--

538
00:52:12,462 --> 00:52:15,488
mighty Agamem non
of Mycenae.

539
00:52:15,599 --> 00:52:17,726
Agamem non!
[ All ]
Agamem non!

540
00:52:19,369 --> 00:52:22,827
Can we agree to unite
in time of war?

541
00:52:24,508 --> 00:52:27,409
What do you say,
Odysseus?
I have a family.

542
00:52:27,511 --> 00:52:31,572
I'd rather plow a field
and sow it with salt
than go to war.

543
00:52:31,681 --> 00:52:34,081
[ Sighs ]
And you, Achilles?

544
00:52:35,485 --> 00:52:38,784
Some of us may prefer
a long and quiet life
at home.

545
00:52:38,889 --> 00:52:41,221
I, for one,
would live it short...

546
00:52:41,324 --> 00:52:44,225
if I knew I could die
with a taste of glory
on my lips.

547
00:52:44,327 --> 00:52:47,455
You will have it short
if one of us takes Helen.

548
00:52:47,564 --> 00:52:49,691
[ Scoffs, Chuckles ]

549
00:52:51,134 --> 00:52:53,034
And yet,

550
00:52:53,136 --> 00:52:56,435
perhaps this is the way
that we can unite
as Agamemnon wishes.

551
00:52:56,540 --> 00:52:59,441
Good Odysseus,
the wisest of us all.

552
00:52:59,543 --> 00:53:02,944
[ Scoffs ]
Tell us, a wise one,
what do you propose?

553
00:53:03,046 --> 00:53:04,946
Two things.

554
00:53:05,048 --> 00:53:08,381
First,
we swear an oath.

555
00:53:08,485 --> 00:53:10,385
What sort
of oath?

556
00:53:10,487 --> 00:53:12,387
Whoever takes Helen...

557
00:53:12,489 --> 00:53:17,449
can trust that we will defend
that man's sole right to her
with our lives.

558
00:53:17,561 --> 00:53:21,463
The rest must be content
to admire her from afar.

559
00:53:21,565 --> 00:53:23,465
And second?

560
00:53:23,567 --> 00:53:27,469
We cast lots.
The winner takes the bride.

561
00:53:27,571 --> 00:53:29,869
Never!

562
00:53:32,108 --> 00:53:34,008
Who--

563
00:53:34,110 --> 00:53:37,079
What gives you the right
to agree on such a thing?

564
00:53:38,682 --> 00:53:41,276
The right of one man
to one vote.

565
00:53:41,384 --> 00:53:44,979
Who in the world
has ever heard of that?
There is no such thing.

566
00:53:46,489 --> 00:53:48,457
Then we begin here.

567
00:53:51,161 --> 00:53:53,129
Who swears the oath?

568
00:54:05,742 --> 00:54:10,679
Agamemnon, as we two
are the only ones
who are married,

569
00:54:10,780 --> 00:54:12,907
how do you suggest
we cast the lots?

570
00:54:15,085 --> 00:54:17,417
Given this noble
assem blage,

571
00:54:17,520 --> 00:54:19,488
I would say our seals.

572
00:55:14,411 --> 00:55:16,311
Closest to the jar...

573
00:55:16,413 --> 00:55:19,007
may claim his bride.

574
00:55:55,952 --> 00:55:57,920
Menelaus.

575
00:56:32,555 --> 00:56:35,388
What sayyou, my brother?

576
00:56:38,361 --> 00:56:40,329
I say the gods have spoken.

577
00:56:45,769 --> 00:56:50,331
And each man here
would be wise
to keep his oath...

578
00:56:50,440 --> 00:56:53,568
or face the everlasting wrath
of Mount Olympus.

579
00:56:56,012 --> 00:56:58,981
[ Giggling ]

580
00:57:04,053 --> 00:57:06,954
Your daughter
is so lovely.

581
00:57:07,056 --> 00:57:08,956
[ Chuckles ]

582
00:57:09,058 --> 00:57:11,117
She reminds me of you.

583
00:57:11,227 --> 00:57:13,787
[ Giggling Continues ]

584
00:57:13,897 --> 00:57:15,865
So long ago.

585
00:57:17,901 --> 00:57:20,131
I phigenia, come.

586
00:57:20,236 --> 00:57:22,704
Say good night to your aunt.

587
00:57:22,806 --> 00:57:24,706
Have you been bouncing?

588
00:57:24,808 --> 00:57:26,708
Ohh!

589
00:57:26,810 --> 00:57:28,778
Give your aunt a kiss.

590
00:57:31,815 --> 00:57:34,545
[ Chuckles ]

591
00:57:34,651 --> 00:57:36,619
Go to bed.
Quickly.

592
00:57:40,123 --> 00:57:44,150
Making a child so sweet
might be reason enough to live.

593
00:57:45,228 --> 00:57:47,321
You have many reasons,
Helen.

594
00:57:50,400 --> 00:57:53,563
Tomorrow you will marry
my husband's brother.

595
00:57:53,670 --> 00:57:56,366
We'll be sisters
and sisters-in-law both.

596
00:57:59,409 --> 00:58:01,570
Yes.

597
00:58:01,678 --> 00:58:03,646
They are hard men.

598
00:58:04,681 --> 00:58:06,706
But it is possible to love them.

599
00:58:23,266 --> 00:58:25,166
Paris?

600
00:58:25,268 --> 00:58:27,168
Father asked to see you.

601
00:58:27,270 --> 00:58:29,238
Hmph.

602
00:58:34,043 --> 00:58:36,011
He's sending you to Sparta.

603
00:58:37,514 --> 00:58:39,948
Why?

604
00:58:40,049 --> 00:58:43,951
Because he wants you
to take a message
to the new king Menelaus,

605
00:58:44,053 --> 00:58:47,784
younger brother
of High King Agamemnon
of Mycenae.

606
00:58:47,891 --> 00:58:51,520
High king?
Some sort of
supreme ruler, is he?

607
00:58:52,996 --> 00:58:55,226
That's right.

608
00:58:55,331 --> 00:58:58,232
And now he's talking more
against Troy.

609
00:58:58,334 --> 00:59:00,234
Why?

610
00:59:00,336 --> 00:59:04,170
Because we control access
to the silks and spices
of Byzantium.

611
00:59:04,274 --> 00:59:06,174
[ Scoffs ]

612
00:59:06,276 --> 00:59:08,176
What?

613
00:59:08,278 --> 00:59:10,473
I just can't believe
people go to war
over nutmeg.

614
00:59:12,815 --> 00:59:15,807
Well, they do, Paris,
and you'd better
get used to it.

615
00:59:15,919 --> 00:59:19,411
Where is he now,
this high king of theirs?

616
00:59:21,190 --> 00:59:23,158
Don't know.

617
00:59:28,665 --> 00:59:33,398
Agamemnon's in Sparta
for the funeral of Tyndareus
and the crowning of Menelaus,

618
00:59:33,503 --> 00:59:36,404
and when I get there
it will appear that I've been
sent to drive a wedge...

619
00:59:36,506 --> 00:59:38,406
between the brothers,

620
00:59:38,508 --> 00:59:41,204
who will then kill me
and put my head on a spike.

621
00:59:41,311 --> 00:59:44,405
Then Troy will be rid of me,
Cassandra will be redeemed...

622
00:59:44,514 --> 00:59:47,415
and you can get back to being
the sole heir to the throne.

623
00:59:47,517 --> 00:59:49,348
Am I close?

624
00:59:49,452 --> 00:59:51,283
You're being a fool.

625
00:59:51,387 --> 00:59:53,355
Look me in the eye and say that.

626
00:59:53,456 --> 00:59:55,549
Look me in the eye.

627
00:59:59,862 --> 01:00:05,198
Brother, if the gods
have divined it, so be it.

628
01:00:13,376 --> 01:00:16,277
[ Winds Whistling ]

629
01:00:16,379 --> 01:00:18,279
Such strong winds,
my lord.

630
01:00:18,381 --> 01:00:20,781
The gods must have
hurried us here.

631
01:00:20,883 --> 01:00:22,783
Yes, it would seem.

632
01:00:22,885 --> 01:00:24,785
They must favor
your mission.

633
01:00:24,887 --> 01:00:26,787
I wouldn't
count on it.

634
01:00:26,889 --> 01:00:28,652
Oh.

635
01:00:31,060 --> 01:00:33,460
Helen,
I'm the obedient wife,

636
01:00:33,563 --> 01:00:35,463
but even I will tellyou...

637
01:00:35,565 --> 01:00:38,466
he's taken this oath
too far.

638
01:00:38,568 --> 01:00:41,332
When you were a child
and Father punishedyou,

639
01:00:41,437 --> 01:00:44,565
you woul d always
com e back fi ghti ng.

640
01:00:46,776 --> 01:00:49,074
Why aren't you
fighting now?

641
01:00:50,813 --> 01:00:53,714
I've caused such grief
and destruction.

642
01:00:53,816 --> 01:00:57,843
Helen, you did not ask
to be kidnapped.

643
01:00:57,954 --> 01:01:00,821
Nor rescued,
for that matter.

644
01:01:02,892 --> 01:01:04,917
It's not your fault.

645
01:01:12,001 --> 01:01:14,902
[ Whispers ]
It's Paris ofTroy.

646
01:01:15,004 --> 01:01:16,972
Bring him here.

647
01:01:23,680 --> 01:01:26,274
You don't know.

648
01:01:26,382 --> 01:01:28,282
Why do you
have to do this?

649
01:01:28,384 --> 01:01:31,911
Menelaus commands it.
I don't do it
for Agamemnon.

650
01:01:32,021 --> 01:01:34,546
Ten thousand men
have sworn their lives...

651
01:01:34,657 --> 01:01:37,558
to defend
the right of Menelaus
to have me.

652
01:01:37,660 --> 01:01:39,958
Agamemnon believes
the king...

653
01:01:40,063 --> 01:01:42,463
should seek proof
of my worth.

654
01:01:42,565 --> 01:01:45,466
How can you let them
treat you like this?

655
01:01:45,568 --> 01:01:47,798
They can look
all they want,

656
01:01:47,904 --> 01:01:49,872
but they'll
never see me.

657
01:01:53,509 --> 01:01:56,478
[ Crowd Chattering, Murmuring ]

658
01:02:19,402 --> 01:02:22,860
[ Men Shouting Approval ]

659
01:02:26,109 --> 01:02:28,270
Truly magnificent.

660
01:02:28,377 --> 01:02:30,277
Breathtaking.

661
01:02:30,379 --> 01:02:33,212
[ Murmuring, Shouting Continue ]

662
01:03:38,281 --> 01:03:41,876
- [ Grunting ]
- Wait! Wait! Wait! We come in peace!

663
01:03:43,820 --> 01:03:45,788
I'll be fine.

664
01:05:01,898 --> 01:05:04,162
He seeks peace,
my brother.

665
01:05:04,267 --> 01:05:06,827
There is no peace
with Troy.

666
01:05:08,537 --> 01:05:11,028
He bears a letter
from their king.

667
01:05:12,241 --> 01:05:14,209
To whom
is it addressed?

668
01:05:41,404 --> 01:05:44,771
[ Crowd Murmuring ]

669
01:05:53,382 --> 01:05:55,714
Do not shame me,
brother.

670
01:05:57,887 --> 01:06:00,515
Troy seeks to align
with Sparta...

671
01:06:01,757 --> 01:06:03,725
and Sparta alone.

672
01:06:06,729 --> 01:06:10,130
They have sent him
to drive a wedge
between us.

673
01:06:10,232 --> 01:06:13,463
We can let nothing
divide the blood
of the house of Atreus.

674
01:06:13,569 --> 01:06:17,027
But not now. Not here.

675
01:06:20,409 --> 01:06:22,809
Let him remain,
freely speaking...

676
01:06:22,912 --> 01:06:28,214
until we know enough ofTroy
to find a way
inside its golden walls.

677
01:06:33,923 --> 01:06:38,724
The weight of a crown
has made my little brother
wise beyond my expectations.

678
01:06:38,828 --> 01:06:41,319
[ Laughing, Chattering Resume ]

679
01:06:51,707 --> 01:06:54,676
[ Sniffling ]

680
01:07:10,459 --> 01:07:12,927
[ Winds Whistling ]

681
01:07:51,434 --> 01:07:53,402
Catch me, Theseus.

682
01:07:55,037 --> 01:07:57,005
Catch me, Pollux.

683
01:07:57,106 --> 01:07:58,767
[ Gasps ]

684
01:08:01,277 --> 01:08:03,245
You.

685
01:08:04,580 --> 01:08:06,548
I've seen you.

686
01:08:07,716 --> 01:08:09,616
In the pool.

687
01:08:09,718 --> 01:08:12,482
You saw too.

688
01:08:13,589 --> 01:08:15,420
I've come for you.

689
01:08:15,524 --> 01:08:17,583
It's too late.

690
01:08:19,962 --> 01:08:21,862
The gods decree it.

691
01:08:21,964 --> 01:08:25,695
Aphrodite herself.
[ Helen ]
Then the gods torment me.

692
01:08:25,801 --> 01:08:28,964
How can you say that?

693
01:08:29,071 --> 01:08:32,268
When I 'm there with them,
I feel nothing.

694
01:08:33,375 --> 01:08:37,709
Naked i n front of
a hundred kings-- nothing.

695
01:08:39,748 --> 01:08:41,648
But then tonight,

696
01:08:41,750 --> 01:08:43,718
when I saw you,

697
01:08:45,254 --> 01:08:48,155
something began to
tear away my shield,

698
01:08:48,257 --> 01:08:50,987
to expose the one thing
that I cannot endure.

699
01:08:54,330 --> 01:08:55,991
Hope.

700
01:08:56,098 --> 01:08:58,658
[ Sighs ]

701
01:08:58,767 --> 01:09:00,735
Have it now.

702
01:09:04,707 --> 01:09:07,175
I love you.
[ Gasps, Sobs ]

703
01:09:16,118 --> 01:09:18,586
Loving me
kills people.

704
01:09:18,687 --> 01:09:22,714
It destroys families,
causes such grief
you cannot imagine.

705
01:09:25,427 --> 01:09:27,691
I've imagined you
all these years.

706
01:09:29,064 --> 01:09:32,033
And now I've found you,
I cannot let you go.

707
01:09:34,236 --> 01:09:36,204
I will never leave you.

708
01:09:37,706 --> 01:09:40,675
The day I do
is the day I die.

709
01:09:58,427 --> 01:10:00,395
Go away.

710
01:10:03,332 --> 01:10:05,232
Leave me.

711
01:10:05,334 --> 01:10:07,632
You must never see me again.

712
01:10:17,279 --> 01:10:19,179
[ Groans ]

713
01:10:19,281 --> 01:10:22,182
You consort with a Trojan,
an enemy of Sparta.

714
01:10:22,284 --> 01:10:25,185
Do you want
to be put to death?
Yes, I do!

715
01:10:25,287 --> 01:10:27,187
[ Trembling ]

716
01:10:27,289 --> 01:10:30,258
What's happened to you?
I've become visible.

717
01:10:31,627 --> 01:10:34,027
You're not making sense
about anything.

718
01:10:34,129 --> 01:10:37,030
You meet some envoy,
and before you--
No!

719
01:10:37,132 --> 01:10:39,032
I didn't
just meet him.

720
01:10:39,134 --> 01:10:42,365
I've loved him foryears,
before you even
married Agamemnon.

721
01:10:42,471 --> 01:10:44,371
That can't be possible.

722
01:10:44,473 --> 01:10:46,441
It's not true,
is it?

723
01:10:49,478 --> 01:10:51,446
What's going to happen?

724
01:10:53,148 --> 01:10:57,209
I heard
Agamemnon and Menelaus
talk of Troy.

725
01:10:57,319 --> 01:10:59,287
And?

726
01:11:01,757 --> 01:11:05,659
Tomorrow they will ask
the envoy about his city.

727
01:11:05,761 --> 01:11:09,162
When Agamemnon has learned
all he needs to know,

728
01:11:09,265 --> 01:11:11,825
we will return to Mycenae
and Menelaus--

729
01:11:11,934 --> 01:11:13,902
Will kill him.

730
01:11:22,444 --> 01:11:24,412
You did well tonight.

731
01:11:25,614 --> 01:11:27,514
The kings were pleased.

732
01:11:27,616 --> 01:11:30,176
Until the envoy
arrived.

733
01:11:30,286 --> 01:11:32,254
Yes.

734
01:11:36,959 --> 01:11:38,927
Why is he here?

735
01:11:40,296 --> 01:11:42,423
That makes
no matter.

736
01:11:44,633 --> 01:11:46,760
Did he come
bearing tribute?

737
01:11:48,904 --> 01:11:52,431
There is no tribute
that compares with you.

738
01:11:52,541 --> 01:11:54,975
You are a generous man.

739
01:11:55,077 --> 01:11:57,045
No, I'm a lucky man.

740
01:12:04,219 --> 01:12:07,120
[ Giggling ]

741
01:12:19,268 --> 01:12:22,169
[Paris ]
You mean stealing's
not a crime in Sparta?

742
01:12:22,271 --> 01:12:25,172
[ Menelaus ]
Being caught is the crime,
always.

743
01:12:25,274 --> 01:12:28,675
There was a boy--
young, no more than 1 0.

744
01:12:28,777 --> 01:12:31,678
He stole a fox
and hid it
under his cloak.

745
01:12:31,780 --> 01:12:33,907
He died
while being questioned,

746
01:12:34,016 --> 01:12:35,916
and when they removed
his cloak...

747
01:12:36,018 --> 01:12:40,921
they found he'd let the fox
gnaw through his body
rather than reveal his theft.

748
01:12:41,023 --> 01:12:43,423
Such boys
make good soldiers.

749
01:12:43,525 --> 01:12:45,425
Yes, they do.

750
01:12:45,527 --> 01:12:48,121
We train them
from the age of seven.

751
01:12:49,198 --> 01:12:51,758
Ours learn to tame horses
from a young age.

752
01:12:51,867 --> 01:12:55,098
You must visit our stables
whilst you are here.

753
01:12:55,204 --> 01:12:58,264
They're not as grand
as your own, I'm sure.

754
01:13:04,546 --> 01:13:06,912
I have heard people say...

755
01:13:07,015 --> 01:13:09,381
that the walls ofTroy
are made ofgold.

756
01:13:09,485 --> 01:13:11,976
Is this really true?

757
01:13:12,087 --> 01:13:13,987
No.

758
01:13:14,089 --> 01:13:15,989
But they are beautiful.

759
01:13:16,091 --> 01:13:19,788
[ Clytem nestra ]
I phigenia, where are you?

760
01:13:19,895 --> 01:13:22,227
Perhaps one day I wi I l
see the walls ofT roy
for myself.

761
01:13:22,331 --> 01:13:23,923
[ Gasps ]

762
01:13:24,032 --> 01:13:27,468
Ah! I found you!
[ Giggling ]

763
01:14:08,544 --> 01:14:11,513
No man can possess
all he desires.

764
01:14:14,516 --> 01:14:16,484
Calchas!

765
01:14:18,153 --> 01:14:20,121
My lord?

766
01:14:24,259 --> 01:14:26,159
My wife tells me...

767
01:14:26,261 --> 01:14:29,230
that no man
can claim the world.

768
01:14:30,365 --> 01:14:32,333
What say the gods?

769
01:14:36,605 --> 01:14:38,664
Olympus favors
the high king...

770
01:14:38,774 --> 01:14:42,073
who one day will rule
the entire Aegean.

771
01:14:50,953 --> 01:14:53,513
You may bear
my children,

772
01:14:53,622 --> 01:14:56,523
but never again
will you interfere
with my affairs.

773
01:14:56,625 --> 01:14:58,593
Is that understood?

774
01:15:33,529 --> 01:15:36,020
- [ Grunting ]
- Come with me!

775
01:15:36,131 --> 01:15:39,589
You! And you!
Let's go!
[ Woman Screaming ]

776
01:15:39,701 --> 01:15:41,464
Quiet!
Let's go!

777
01:15:41,570 --> 01:15:43,470
I thought we were here
to make peace.

778
01:15:43,572 --> 01:15:45,938
We like
making peace.
Yes. A lot.

779
01:15:46,041 --> 01:15:47,941
The Greeks
have other ideas.

780
01:15:48,043 --> 01:15:49,943
What sort of ideas? 

781
01:15:50,045 --> 01:15:55,244
Like cut off our heads,
put them on pikes,
let birds eat our eyes.

782
01:15:55,350 --> 01:15:57,079
That sort of thing.

783
01:16:20,909 --> 01:16:23,139
Prince Paris of Troy,

784
01:16:23,245 --> 01:16:26,214
my king bids you
a fond good night.

785
01:16:35,524 --> 01:16:38,084
[ Grunting ]

786
01:16:42,197 --> 01:16:44,825
Aah!
[ Groaning ]

787
01:17:07,222 --> 01:17:09,782
Man those oars!
Get to the turret!

788
01:17:10,993 --> 01:17:13,655
Go now.
You're free.

789
01:17:18,934 --> 01:17:20,902
Without you?

790
01:17:24,239 --> 01:17:26,537
You have my love.

791
01:17:26,642 --> 01:17:29,133
Without you
I have nothing.

792
01:17:35,250 --> 01:17:37,150
My lord!
My lord!

793
01:17:37,252 --> 01:17:39,220
The tide
begins to turn!

794
01:17:42,124 --> 01:17:44,024
Menelaus is shamed,

795
01:17:44,126 --> 01:17:47,095
but he fears to harm me.

796
01:17:48,530 --> 01:17:50,498
Now go.

797
01:17:52,367 --> 01:17:55,632
I beg you!
Please go!

798
01:17:56,672 --> 01:17:58,936
My lord!
The wi nd is up!

799
01:18:03,345 --> 01:18:05,313
Please.

800
01:18:10,018 --> 01:18:12,213
Please.

801
01:18:15,057 --> 01:18:17,025
Make way, men!

802
01:18:18,860 --> 01:18:21,260
[ Crewmen Shouting,
Chattering]

803
01:18:28,336 --> 01:18:30,304
[ Crewman ]
Ready oars!

804
01:18:31,473 --> 01:18:33,566
Ready? Pull!

805
01:18:35,143 --> 01:18:37,111
Ready? Pull!

806
01:18:41,950 --> 01:18:44,384
Ready? Pul l!

807
01:18:46,922 --> 01:18:49,152
No.

808
01:18:54,196 --> 01:18:56,164
[ Crewman ]
Hold oars!

809
01:19:02,871 --> 01:19:04,839
Make way!

810
01:19:12,047 --> 01:19:14,015
What have we done?

811
01:19:22,457 --> 01:19:25,426
[ Crowd Shouting, Cheering ]

812
01:19:50,452 --> 01:19:52,545
[ Crowd ]
Ohh!

813
01:19:52,654 --> 01:19:56,021
[ Crowd Cheering, Whistling ]
Wel I fought, Croesus.

814
01:20:01,029 --> 01:20:03,862
[ Crowd Chanting ]
Achilles! Achilles!

815
01:20:03,965 --> 01:20:05,865
[ Chanting Continues ]
Your news precedes you.

816
01:20:05,967 --> 01:20:08,868
As the gods are my witness,
I will kill that man.
You can be sure of it.

817
01:20:08,970 --> 01:20:11,530
You brought dishonor
on yourself and shame
to the house of Atreus.

818
01:20:11,640 --> 01:20:14,871
I'll have the Trojan's head
on a spike!

819
01:20:14,976 --> 01:20:17,877
Not without my help.
Ah, yes.

820
01:20:17,979 --> 01:20:21,574
Well, as always,
I must bear the weight
of your shadow.

821
01:20:21,683 --> 01:20:23,981
You're a smudge
on history's ledger,
Menelaus,

822
01:20:24,085 --> 01:20:25,985
but you are my brother.

823
01:20:26,087 --> 01:20:28,487
What's more,
the kings of the Aegean
have sworn an oath.

824
01:20:28,590 --> 01:20:30,490
To unite,
as I recall.

825
01:20:30,592 --> 01:20:33,993
The oath did not place you
in command of me,
of my army, or any other--

826
01:20:34,095 --> 01:20:37,223
Do not incur my wrath,
little brother. Do not.

827
01:20:37,332 --> 01:20:39,892
These are my terms.

828
01:20:40,001 --> 01:20:42,094
You may have the Trojan...

829
01:20:42,204 --> 01:20:44,104
and your whore.

830
01:20:44,206 --> 01:20:46,106
I will take Troy.

831
01:20:46,208 --> 01:20:48,608
You will share
no spoils--

832
01:20:48,710 --> 01:20:50,610
not a scrap
of broken clay,

833
01:20:50,712 --> 01:20:53,340
not an ingot
of their basest metal.

834
01:20:54,115 --> 01:20:55,514
Agreed?

835
01:20:55,617 --> 01:20:58,484
I am your brother--
Do you agree?

836
01:20:58,587 --> 01:21:01,078
[ Crowd Quiets ]

837
01:21:07,229 --> 01:21:10,130
What makes you think
the kings will unite
behind you?

838
01:21:10,232 --> 01:21:12,564
The gods have written it.

839
01:21:12,667 --> 01:21:16,569
And you know for certain
they favor you in this?
For certain!

840
01:21:20,709 --> 01:21:23,678
[ Crewmen Shouting ]

841
01:21:39,761 --> 01:21:41,160
Save him!

842
01:21:42,063 --> 01:21:43,894
Swim, Clemyetus!

843
01:21:43,965 --> 01:21:45,091
Throw me the line!

844
01:21:45,166 --> 01:21:46,633
Reach for me!

845
01:21:49,504 --> 01:21:51,472
Aah!

846
01:21:53,108 --> 01:21:55,804
[ Screaming ]

847
01:22:35,583 --> 01:22:37,551
[ Sighs ]

848
01:22:44,793 --> 01:22:46,761
Two months.

849
01:22:48,129 --> 01:22:50,188
The wind remains against us.

850
01:22:50,298 --> 01:22:52,198
The men grow impatient!

851
01:22:52,300 --> 01:22:55,292
I grow impatient, Achilles.

852
01:22:58,306 --> 01:23:00,206
Calchas.

853
01:23:00,308 --> 01:23:02,208
My lord.

854
01:23:05,580 --> 01:23:08,481
When will the winds
blow with us?

855
01:23:08,583 --> 01:23:10,551
What say the gods?

856
01:23:15,423 --> 01:23:17,391
Speak, seer.

857
01:23:19,361 --> 01:23:21,261
What must I do?

858
01:23:21,363 --> 01:23:23,331
A terrible thing.

859
01:23:27,369 --> 01:23:29,337
Tell me.

860
01:23:31,439 --> 01:23:33,839
I command you.

861
01:23:33,942 --> 01:23:37,105
The goddess Artemis
asks foryour daughter.

862
01:23:40,982 --> 01:23:42,882
In trade for fair wind,

863
01:23:42,984 --> 01:23:45,452
Artemis demands
your daughter's life...

864
01:23:47,455 --> 01:23:49,423
here, on this altar.

865
01:24:03,371 --> 01:24:06,863
And this...
will satisfy the goddess?

866
01:24:09,277 --> 01:24:11,245
But you must hold
the knife.

867
01:24:13,048 --> 01:24:15,016
The gods demand it.

868
01:24:20,388 --> 01:24:22,356
Of course they do.

869
01:24:52,921 --> 01:24:55,890
The winds
will soon be with us.

870
01:24:56,925 --> 01:24:58,825
Pitch!

871
01:24:58,927 --> 01:25:00,895
Oh!

872
01:25:04,265 --> 01:25:06,165
[ Giggles ]

873
01:25:06,267 --> 01:25:08,565
Okay, ready?

874
01:25:08,670 --> 01:25:10,638
Ready?

875
01:25:26,154 --> 01:25:28,486
[ Laughing ]

876
01:25:45,273 --> 01:25:47,741
[ Continues Giggling, Laughing ]

